data.content:
This is the **C# 14 `Span<T>` overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions mean `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` method **cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression is compiled/interpreted.

## How to fix it

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Call Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

Any of these prevent the compiler from picking the span overload. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` instead of `arr.Reverse()`.
